DAX Index Climbs, Posts Weekly Gain; Deutsche Bank, Lanxess Rise

-- B y   J u l i e   C r u z
-- 
2011-04-01T15:53:02Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-01/deutsche-post-kabel-deutschland-rwe-german-equity-preview.html
German stocks rose, with the
benchmark  DAX Index (DAX)  posting a second weekly advance, after a
report showed the U.S. added more jobs than forecast in March
and the  unemployment rate  unexpectedly fell to a two-year low.  Munich Re and  Deutsche Bank AG (DBK)  followed a rally in
financial shares across  Europe .  Symrise AG (SY1)  jumped 4.4 percent as
Deutsche Bank upgraded the stock to “buy” from “hold.”
 Lanxess AG (LXS)  climbed 3.7 percent after increasing prices for its
rubber products.  The DAX gained 2 percent to 7,179.81 at the 5:30 p.m. close
in  Frankfurt , posting a weekly increase of 3.4 percent. The
measure has climbed 10 percent since this year’s low on March 16
as investors speculated that  Japan  will prevent a meltdown at
its earthquake-damaged nuclear power plant and the U.S., the
U.K. and  France  mounted airstrikes against Muammar Qaddafi’s
armed forces in  Libya . The broader  HDAX Index (HDAX)  advanced 1.9
percent today.  “The trend of improving jobs numbers continues, providing
positive sentiment and further cause for optimism in equities,”
said Daniel Weston, Munich-based portfolio adviser at Schroeder
Equities GmbH.  U.S. payrolls rose by 216,000 workers last month after a
revised 194,000 increase the prior month, the Labor Department
said today in  Washington . Economists projected a March gain of
190,000, according to the median estimate in a Bloomberg News
survey. The jobless rate dropped to 8.8 percent.  Manufacturing Report  In  China , manufacturing growth accelerated for the first
time in four months, easing concern that monetary tightening may
lead to a slowdown in the world’s second-biggest economy. The
Purchasing Managers’ Index from the China Federation of
Logistics and Purchasing rose to 53.4 in March from 52.2 in
February. A separate PMI by HSBC Holdings Plc also gained.  Munich Re , the world’s largest reinsurer, gained 2.8
percent to 114.15 euros, while Deutsche Bank,  Germany ’s biggest
bank, advanced 3.1 percent to 42.75 euros. Banking and insurance
shares rose across Europe today after Ireland ruled out forcing
bondholders to share the cost of rescuing its lenders.  Symrise, the maker that supplies ingredients for Britney
Spears perfume, surged 4.4 percent to 21.60 euros, the highest
closing price this year. Deutsche Bank analysts including
Virginie Boucher-Ferte upgraded the stock, saying Symrise’s
earnings and sales will increase in the first quarter.  Lanxess rallied 3.7 percent to 54.71 euros, erasing
yesterday’s drop. Germany’s biggest publicly traded specialty
chemicals producer raised prices for synthetic rubber products
Perbunan and Krynac by as much as 250 euros ($354) a ton because
of higher raw-material and transport costs.  MTU Aero Engines Holding AG (MTX)  climbed 2.2 percent to 48.91
euros as the company projected about 300 million euros in
revenue from its share in a contract to equip 150 A320neo
aircraft with propulsion systems.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Julie Cruz in Frankfurt at 
